  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Auden Cordell (AC), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>The questions that come up most often from readers of this site, with plain-language answers. For specific advice about your case, consult a licensed product liability attorney in your state.</p>

  <h2>1. What is the difference between strict liability and negligence in a product case?</h2>

  <p>In a negligence claim, the plaintiff has to prove the defendant was careless &mdash; that the defendant breached a duty of care and that the breach caused the injury. In a strict liability product claim, the plaintiff does not have to prove carelessness; it is enough to prove that the product was defective when it left the defendant's control and that the defect caused the injury. The defendant's level of care is legally irrelevant. This is the central reason product liability cases settle for more than equivalent negligence claims: the plaintiff's prima facie case is simpler and harder to defeat at summary judgment. Most states allow plaintiffs to plead negligence and strict liability in the alternative.</p>

  <h2>2. Should I join a class action or file an individual claim?</h2>

  <p>Generally, an individual injury claim recovers more per claimant than a class action because the individual case captures your specific medical bills, lost wages, and pain and suffering. Class actions are most appropriate for low-value-per-claimant harms (a defective dishwasher, undisclosed ingredient in a consumer product, false advertising) where individual litigation would not be economically viable. For a personal injury, your individual claim is almost always worth more than a class share. A mass-tort MDL is a hybrid: individual cases are coordinated for discovery efficiency but resolved individually, preserving the higher per-claimant recovery.</p>

  <h2>3. What is the statute of repose, and does it bar my claim?</h2>

  <p>A statute of repose caps a manufacturer's product-liability exposure at a fixed period after the product was first sold, regardless of when the injury occurred. About a third of states have one; the period is typically 10&ndash;15 years. So if you were injured by a 20-year-old industrial machine in a state with a 12-year statute of repose, the manufacturer is not liable under strict liability, regardless of how clearly the defect caused the injury. Several states carve out exceptions for products marketed with a longer expected useful life (heavy industrial equipment, building components). The statute of repose is distinct from the statute of limitations, which runs from the injury or discovery; you can be timely under the statute of limitations and still barred by the statute of repose.</p>

  <h2>4. Is a product recall relevant to my case?</h2>

  <p>Yes, significantly. A CPSC, FDA, or NHTSA recall is admissible evidence that the manufacturer (or at least the regulator) considered the product defective. A pre-injury recall strengthens your strict-liability case substantially because it removes any plausible defense that the defect was unknown. A post-injury recall is still useful evidence of defect but allows the manufacturer to argue it acted responsibly upon discovery. Either way, if the product you were injured by has been recalled, locate the recall notice and preserve it.</p>

  <h2>5. What is joint and several liability, and why does it matter?</h2>

  <p>Joint and several liability is a rule that allows a plaintiff to recover the full judgment from any one defendant in the chain of distribution, even if that defendant was only partly at fault. It matters in product liability because the chain often includes a manufacturer (well-insured), a distributor, and a retailer (less well-insured), and the defendant the plaintiff can collect from may not be the most culpable one. About half of states have moved to "modified" comparative-fault rules that limit joint-and-several to defendants over a certain fault threshold (often 50%). State-by-state variation is significant.</p>

  <h2>6. The manufacturer is a multinational based overseas. Can I still sue?</h2>

  <p>Usually yes, but the procedure is harder. A foreign manufacturer that distributes products into the United States is generally subject to personal jurisdiction in any state where its products caused injury (the "stream of commerce" doctrine, though the Supreme Court's recent decisions have tightened the analysis). Service of process under the Hague Convention can take six months to a year. Discovery is harder. Collection on a judgment can require ancillary proceedings overseas. For these reasons, plaintiffs' counsel often sue the U.S. subsidiary, the U.S. distributor, and the U.S. retailer alongside the foreign parent &mdash; the U.S. defendants are easier to collect from and joint-and-several liability fills any gap.</p>

  <h2>7. How are product liability attorneys paid?</h2>

  <p>Almost universally on contingency. The standard fee is one-third (33.33%) of the recovery if the case settles before suit is filed and 40% if it goes to suit or trial; some firms use a flat one-third regardless. Expenses (expert fees, deposition costs, court filing fees) are advanced by the firm and reimbursed from the recovery, typically off the top before the contingency calculation. If there is no recovery, the client owes nothing for legal fees, and most firms also waive expense reimbursement on losses. The contingency model is what makes product liability accessible to ordinary consumers: you do not need money up front to bring a case.</p>

  <h2>8. Why do product liability cases cost so much in expert witness fees?</h2>

  <p>Product cases live or die on expert testimony. A typical case may require a design engineer to opine on the defect, a manufacturing-process expert to explain how the defect arose, a treating physician and a life-care planner for damages, and a vocational economist for lost earning capacity. Each may charge $400&ndash;$1,000/hour and the cumulative cost of expert work in a substantial product case can run $50,000&ndash;$500,000. The plaintiff's firm typically advances these costs against the contingency recovery; if the case loses, the firm absorbs the loss. The economics is why plaintiff-side product liability firms screen cases aggressively.</p>

  <h2>9. Do the rules really vary that much state-to-state?</h2>

  <p>Yes. State variation is one of the most underappreciated features of product liability law. Some states recognize both consumer-expectation and risk-utility tests for design defect; some only one. Some apply joint and several liability fully; some only above a fault threshold; some have abolished it. Some cap non-economic damages or punitive damages; most do not. Some have a statute of repose; most do not. Some have abolished post-sale duty-to-warn doctrines; some embrace them. The same case can be worth twice as much in California or New Jersey as it would be in Texas or Tennessee.</p>

  <h2>10. The product I was injured by was bought used. Am I out of luck?</h2>

  <p>Not necessarily, but it complicates things. Strict liability runs against sellers in the ordinary chain of distribution &mdash; manufacturer, distributor, retailer. A casual second-hand sale (a yard sale, eBay listing by an individual) is generally not in the chain. But the original manufacturer's strict liability for a design or manufacturing defect persists regardless of how many times the product has changed hands; you can still sue the manufacturer. The harder cases are alteration or wear: if the original product is no longer in its original condition because of modifications or normal wear, the defense will argue that the cause of injury is the alteration or wear, not the original defect.</p>

  <h2>11. What if I was using the product in a way it was not designed for?</h2>

  <p>Misuse is a common defense but not always a winning one. The legal standard is "reasonably foreseeable use," not "intended use." Standing on a chair to change a light bulb is a foreseeable misuse of a chair, even if the chair is "intended" only for sitting. Stripping a screw with a power drill is foreseeable misuse of a drill. The manufacturer's duty is to design and warn against reasonably foreseeable misuses. The defense wins only when the misuse is genuinely unforeseeable (using a hair dryer in a bathtub, despite explicit warnings) and a sole proximate cause of the injury.</p>

  <h2>12. How long will a product liability case take?</h2>

  <p>A straightforward individual case settles in 12&ndash;24 months from intake. A case that goes to suit and through discovery typically takes 24&ndash;36 months. A case that goes to trial takes 36&ndash;48 months or longer. Mass-tort MDLs are slower: bellwether trials may not occur for three or four years after MDL formation, and individual claimants outside the bellwether pool may wait five to seven years for resolution. The plaintiff's lawyer can often advance the case faster than the defense would prefer by being aggressive on discovery, but the floor on case duration is set by the complexity of expert workup.</p>

